# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: denotation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer was educated at Eton College and the University of Oxford, after which he studied the philosophy of logical positivism at the University of Vienna.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] From 1933 to 1940 he lectured on philosophy at Christ Church, Oxford.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] During the Second World War Ayer was a Special Operations Executive and MI6 agent.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer was Grote Professor of the Philosophy of Mind and Logic at University College London from 1946 until 1959, after which he returned to Oxford to become Wykeham Professor of Logic at New College.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He was president of the Aristotelian Society from 1951 to 1952 and knighted in 1970.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He was known for his advocacy of humanism, and was the second president of the British Humanist Association (now known as Humanists UK).
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer was born in St John's Wood, in north west London, to Jules Louis Cyprien Ayer and Reine (née Citroen), wealthy parents from continental Europe.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] His mother was from the Dutch-Jewish family that founded the Citroën car company in France; his father was a Swiss Calvinist financier who worked for the Rothschild family, including for their bank and as secretary to Alfred Rothschild.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer was educated at Ascham St Vincent's School, a former boarding preparatory school for boys in the seaside town of Eastbourne in Sussex, where he started boarding at the relatively early age of seven for reasons to do with the First World War, and at Eton College, where he was a King's Scholar.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] At Eton, Ayer first became known for his characteristic bravado and precocity.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Though primarily interested in his intellectual pursuits, he was very keen on sports, particularly rugby, and reputedly played the Eton Wall Game very well.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] In the final examinations at Eton, Ayer came second in his year, and first in classics.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] In his final year, as a member of Eton's senior council, he unsuccessfully campaigned for the abolition of corporal punishment at the school.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He won a classics scholarship to Christ Church, Oxford.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He graduated with a BA with first-class honours.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] After graduating from Oxford, Ayer spent a year in Vienna, returned to England and published his first book, *Language, Truth and Logic*, in 1936.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] This first exposition in English of logical positivism as newly developed by the Vienna Circle, made Ayer at age 26 the *enfant terrible* of British philosophy.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] As a newly famous intellectual, he played a prominent role in the Oxford by-election campaign of 1938.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer campaigned first for the Labour candidate Patrick Gordon Walker, and then for the joint Labour-Liberal "Independent Progressive" candidate Sandie Lindsay, who ran on an anti-appeasement platform against the Conservative candidate, Quintin Hogg, who ran as the appeasement candidate.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] The by-election, held on 27 October 1938, was quite close, with Hogg winning narrowly.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] In the Second World War, Ayer served as an officer in the Welsh Guards, chiefly in intelligence (Special Operations Executive (SOE) and MI6).
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He was commissioned as a second lieutenant into the Welsh Guards from the Officer Cadet Training Unit on 21 September 1940.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] After the war, Ayer briefly returned to the University of Oxford where he became a fellow and Dean of Wadham College.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He then taught philosophy at University College London from 1946 until 1959, during which time he started to appear on radio and television.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He was an extrovert and social mixer who liked dancing and attending clubs in London and New York.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He was also obsessed with sport: he had played rugby for Eton, and was a noted cricketer and a keen supporter of Tottenham Hotspur football team, where he was for many years a season ticket holder.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] For an academic, Ayer was an unusually well-connected figure in his time, with close links to 'high society' and the establishment.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Presiding over Oxford high-tables, he is often described as charming, but could also be intimidating.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer was married four times to three women.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] His first marriage was from 1932 to 1941, to (Grace Isabel) Renée, with whom he had a son – allegedly the son of Ayer's friend and colleague Stuart Hampshire – and a daughter.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] In 1960, Ayer married Alberta Constance (Dee) Wells, with whom he had one son.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] That marriage was dissolved in 1983, and the same year, Ayer married Vanessa Salmon, the former wife of politician Nigel Lawson.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] She died in 1985, and in 1989 Ayer remarried Wells, who survived him.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He also had a daughter with Hollywood columnist Sheilah Graham Westbrook.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] In 1950, Ayer attended the founding meeting of the Congress for Cultural Freedom in West Berlin, though he later said he went only because of the offer of a "free trip".
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He gave a speech on why John Stuart Mill's conceptions of liberty and freedom were still valid in the 20th century.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Together with the historian Hugh Trevor-Roper, Ayer fought against Arthur Koestler and Franz Borkenau, arguing that they were far too dogmatic and extreme in their anti-communism, in fact proposing illiberal measures in the defence of liberty.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Adding to the tension was the location of the congress in West Berlin, together with the fact that the Korean War began on 25 June 1950, the fourth day of the congress, giving a feeling that the world was on the brink of war.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] From 1959 to his retirement in 1978, Ayer held the Wykeham Chair, Professor of Logic at Oxford.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] After his retirement, Ayer taught or lectured several times in the United States, including as a visiting professor at Bard College in 1987.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] At a party that same year held by fashion designer Fernando Sanchez, Ayer confronted Mike Tyson, who was forcing himself upon the then little-known model Naomi Campbell.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] When Ayer demanded that Tyson stop, Tyson reportedly asked, "Do you know who the fuck I am?
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] I'm the heavyweight champion of the world", to which Ayer replied, "And I am the former Wykeham Professor of Logic.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] I suggest that we talk about this like rational men".
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer and Tyson then began to talk, allowing Campbell to slip out.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Gully Wells, Ayer's stepdaughter via Dee Wells, records the same event with some slight variation of detail.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer was also involved in politics, including anti-Vietnam War activism, supporting the Labour Party (and later the Social Democratic Party), chairing the Campaign Against Racial Discrimination in Sport, and serving as president of the Homosexual Law Reform Society.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] In 1978 he was interviewed for Bryan Magee's *Men of Ideas* television show, where he spoke about logical positivism and its legacy, later in 1987 he appeared on Magee's *The Great Philosophers* in an episode centering on Frege, Russell and Modern Logic.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] In 1988, a year before his death, Ayer wrote an article titled "What I saw when I was dead", describing an unusual near-death experience after his heart stopped for four minutes as he choked on smoked salmon.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] From 1980 to 1989 he lived at 51 York Street, Marylebone, where a memorial plaque was unveiled on 19 November 1995.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] In *Language, Truth and Logic* (1936), Ayer presents the verification principle as the only valid basis for philosophy.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Unless logical or empirical verification is possible, statements like "God exists" or "charity is good" are not true or untrue but meaningless, and may thus be excluded or ignored.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Religious language in particular is unverifiable and as such literally nonsense.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Mace's opinion that metaphysics is a form of intellectual poetry.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] The stance that a belief in God denotes no verifiable hypothesis is sometimes referred to as igtheism (for example, by Paul Kurtz).
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] In later years, Ayer reiterated that he did not believe in God and began to call himself an atheist.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He followed in the footsteps of Bertrand Russell by debating religion with the Jesuit scholar Frederick Copleston.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He focuses on propositions of the first class – moral judgements – saying that those of the second class belong to science, those of the third are mere commands, and those of the fourth (which are considered normative ethics as opposed to meta-ethics) are too concrete for ethical philosophy.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer argues that moral judgements cannot be translated into non-ethical, empirical terms and thus cannot be verified; in this he agrees with ethical intuitionists.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] But he differs from intuitionists by discarding appeals to intuition of non-empirical moral truths as "worthless" since the intuition of one person often contradicts that of another.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Between 1945 and 1947, together with Russell and George Orwell, Ayer contributed a series of articles to *Polemic*, a short-lived British *Magazine of Philosophy, Psychology, and Aesthetics* edited by the ex-Communist Humphrey Slater.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer was closely associated with the British humanist movement.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He was an Honorary Associate of the Rationalist Press Association from 1947 until his death.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He was elected a Foreign Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1963.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] In 1965, he became the first president of the Agnostics' Adoption Society and in the same year succeeded Julian Huxley as president of the British Humanist Association, a post he held until 1970.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] In 1968 he edited *The Humanist Outlook*, a collection of essays on the meaning of humanism.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He was one of the signers of the Humanist Manifesto.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer is best known for popularising the verification principle, in particular through his presentation of it in *Language, Truth, and Logic*.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] The principle was at the time at the heart of the debates of the so-called Vienna Circle, which Ayer had visited as a young guest.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Others, including the circle's leading light, Moritz Schlick, were already writing papers on the issue.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer's formulation was that a sentence can be meaningful only if it has verifiable empirical import; otherwise, it is either "analytical" if tautologous or "metaphysical" (i.e. meaningless, or "literally senseless").
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He started to work on the book at the age of 23 and it was published when he was 26.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer's philosophical ideas were deeply influenced by those of the Vienna Circle and David Hume.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] His clear, vibrant and polemical exposition of them makes *Language, Truth and Logic* essential reading on the tenets of logical empiricism; the book is regarded as a classic of 20th-century analytic philosophy and is widely read in philosophy courses around the world.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer wrote two books on the philosopher Bertrand Russell, *Russell and Moore: The Analytic Heritage* (1971) and *Russell* (1972).
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He also wrote an introductory book on the philosophy of David Hume and a short biography of Voltaire.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer was a strong critic of the German philosopher Martin Heidegger.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] As a logical positivist, Ayer was in conflict with Heidegger's vast, overarching theories of existence.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer considered them completely unverifiable through empirical demonstration and logical analysis, and this sort of philosophy an unfortunate strain in modern thought.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He considered Heidegger the worst example of such philosophy, which Ayer believed entirely useless.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] In *Philosophy in the Twentieth Century*, Ayer accuses Heidegger of "surprising ignorance" or "unscrupulous distortion" and "what can fairly be described as charlatanism".
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] In 1972–73, Ayer gave the Gifford Lectures at the University of St Andrews, later published as *The Central Questions of Philosophy*.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] He still believed in the viewpoint he shared with the logical positivists: that large parts of what was traditionally called philosophy—including metaphysics, theology and aesthetics—were not matters that could be judged true or false, and that it was thus meaningless to discuss them.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] In *The Concept of a Person and Other Essays* (1963), Ayer heavily criticised Wittgenstein's private language argument.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer's sense-data theory in *Foundations of Empirical Knowledge* was famously criticised by fellow Oxonian J.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Austin in *Sense and Sensibilia*, a landmark 1950s work of ordinary language philosophy.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer responded in the essay "Has Austin Refuted the Sense-datum Theory?", which can be found in his *Metaphysics and Common Sense* (1969).
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer was awarded a knighthood as Knight Bachelor in the London Gazette on 1 January 1970.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] Ayer's biographer, Ben Rogers, deposited 7 boxes of research material accumulated through the writing process at University College London in 2007.
[src:denotation/a-j-ayer] The material was donated in collaboration with Ayer's family.
[src:denotation/actualism] In analytic philosophy, **actualism** is the view that everything that *is* (i.e., everything that has *being*, in the broadest sense) is actual.
[src:denotation/actualism] Another phrasing of the thesis is that the domain of unrestricted quantification ranges over all and only actual existents.
[src:denotation/actualism] The denial of actualism is **possibilism**, the thesis that there are some entities that are *merely possible*: these entities have being but are not actual and, hence, enjoy a "less robust" sort of being than do actually existing things.
[src:denotation/actualism] An important, but significantly different notion of possibilism known as *modal realism* was developed by the philosopher David Lewis.
[src:denotation/actualism] On Lewis's account, the actual world is identified with the physical universe of which we are all a part.
[src:denotation/actualism] Other possible worlds exist in exactly the same sense as the actual world; they are simply spatio-temporally unrelated to our world, and to each other.
[src:denotation/actualism] Hence, for Lewis, "merely possible" entities—entities that exist in other possible worlds—exist in exactly the same sense as do we in the actual world; to be actual, from the perspective of any given individual *x* in any possible world, is simply to be part of the same world as *x*.
[src:denotation/actualism] Actualists face the problem of explaining why many expressions commonly used in natural language are meaningful and sometimes even true despite the fact that they contain references to non-actual entities.
[src:denotation/actualism] Problematic expressions include names of fictional characters, definite descriptions and intentional attitude reports.
[src:denotation/actualism] Actualists have often responded to this problem by paraphrasing the expressions with apparently problematic ontological commitments into ones that are free of such commitments.
[src:denotation/actualism] Actualism has been challenged by truthmaker theory to explain how truths about what is possible or necessary depend on actuality, i.e. to point out which actual entities can act as truthmakers for them.
[src:denotation/actualism] Popular candidates for this role within an actualist ontology include possible worlds conceived as abstract objects, essences and dispositions.
[src:denotation/actualism] Actualism and possibilism in ethics are two different theories about how future choices affect what the agent should presently do.
[src:denotation/actualism] Actualists assert that it is only relevant what the agent would actually do later for assessing the normative status of an alternative.
[src:denotation/actualism] Possibilists, on the other hand, hold that we should also take into account what the agent could do, even if he wouldn't do it.
[src:denotation/actualism] Consider the statement "Sherlock Holmes exists." This is a false statement about the world, but is usually accepted as representing a possible truth.
[src:denotation/actualism] This contingency is usually described by the statement "there is a possible world in which Sherlock Holmes exists".
[src:denotation/actualism] The possibilist argues that apparent existential claims such as this (that "there are" possible worlds of various sorts) ought to be taken more or less at face value: as stating the *existence* of two or more worlds, only one of which (at the most) can be the actual one.
[src:denotation/actualism] Hence, they argue, there are innumerably many possible worlds other than our own, which exist just as much as ours does.
[src:denotation/actualism] Most actualists will be happy to grant the interpretation of "Sherlock Holmes' existence is possible" in terms of possible worlds.
[src:denotation/actualism] But they argue that the possibilist goes wrong in taking this as a sign that there exist other worlds that are just like ours, except for the fact that we are not actually in them.
[src:denotation/actualism] From an actualist point of view, such as Robert Merrihew Adams', possible worlds are nothing more than fictions created within the actual world.
[src:denotation/actualism] Possible worlds are mere descriptions of ways this world (the actual one) might have been, and nothing else.
[src:denotation/actualism] Thus, as modal constructions, they come in as a handy heuristic device to use with modal logic; as it helps our modal reasoning to imagine ways the world might have been.
[src:denotation/actualism] Thus, the actualist interpretation of "◊p" sees the modality (i.e., "the way" in which it is true) as being de dicto and not entailing any ontological commitment.
[src:denotation/actualism] From a modal realist's point of view, such as Lewis', the proposition "◊p" means that p obtains in at least one other, distinct world that is as real as the one we are in.
[src:denotation/actualism] If a state of affairs is possible, then it really obtains, it physically occurs in at least one world.
[src:denotation/actualism] Therefore, as Lewis is happy to admit, there is a world where someone named Sherlock Holmes lived at 221b Baker Street in Victorian times, there is another world where pigs fly, and there is even another world where both Sherlock Holmes exists and pigs fly.
[src:denotation/actualism] This leaves open the question, of course, of what an actually existing "way the world could be" *is*; and on this question actualists are divided.
[src:denotation/actualism] One of the most popular solutions is to claim, as William Lycan and Adams do, that "possible worlds" talk can be reduced to logical relations amongst consistent and maximally complete *sets of propositions*.
[src:denotation/actualism] "Consistent" here means that none of its propositions contradict one another (if they did, it would not be a *possible* description of the world); "maximally complete" means that the set covers *every* feature of the world.
[src:denotation/actualism] Here the "possible world" which is said to be actual is actual in virtue of *all* its elements being *true* of the world around us.
[src:denotation/actualism] Actualism, the view that being is restricted to actual being, is usually contrasted with possibilism, the view that being also includes possible entities, so-called *possibilia*.
[src:denotation/actualism] But there is a third and even wider-ranging view, Meinongianism, which holds that being includes impossible entities.
[src:denotation/actualism] So actualists disagree with both possibilists and Meinongians whether there are possible objects, e.g. unicorns, while actualists and possibilists disagree with Meinongians whether there are impossible objects, e.g. round squares.
[src:denotation/actualism] The disagreements between these three views touch many areas in philosophy, including the semantics of natural language and the problem of intentionality.
[src:denotation/actualism] This is due to the fact that various expressions commonly used in natural language seem to refer to merely possible and in some cases even impossible objects.
[src:denotation/actualism] Since actualists deny the existence of such objects, it would seem that they are committed to the view that these expressions don't refer to anything and are therefore meaningless.
[src:denotation/actualism] This would be a rather unintuitive consequence of actualism, which is why actualists have proposed different strategies for different types of expressions in order to avoid this conclusion.
[src:denotation/actualism] These strategies usually involve some kind of paraphrase that transforms a sentence with apparently problematic ontological commitments into one that is free of such commitments.
[src:denotation/actualism] Intentional attitude reports about non-actual entities are another type of problematic cases, for example "Peter likes Superman".
[src:denotation/actualism] Possibilists can interpret the intentional attitude, in this case the liking, as a relation between Peter, an actual person, and Superman, a possible person.
[src:denotation/actualism] One actualist solution to this problem involves treating intentional attitudes not as relations between a subject and an object but as properties of the subject.
[src:denotation/actualism] This approach has been termed "adverbialism" since the object of the intentional attitude is seen as a modification of the attitude: "Peter likes superman-ly".
[src:denotation/actualism] This paraphrase succeeds in removing any reference to non-actual entities.
[src:denotation/actualism] Truthmaker theorists hold that truth depends on reality.
[src:denotation/actualism] In the terms of truthmaker theory: a truthbearer (e.g. a proposition) is true because of the existence of its truthmaker (e.g. a fact).
[src:denotation/actualism] Positing a truth without being able to account for its truthmaker violates this principle and has been labeled "ontological cheating".
[src:denotation/actualism] Actualists face the problem of how to account for the truthmakers of modal truths, like "it was possible for the Cuban Missile Crisis to escalate into a full-scale nuclear war", "there could have been purple cows" or "it is necessary that all cows are animals".
[src:denotation/actualism] Actualists have proposed various solutions, but there is no consensus as to which one is the best solution.
[src:denotation/actualism] A well-known account relies on the notion of possible worlds, conceived as actual abstract objects, for example as maximal consistent sets of propositions or of states of affairs.
[src:denotation/actualism] A set of propositions is maximal if, for any statement *p*, either *p* or *not-p* is a member.
[src:denotation/actualism] Possible worlds act as truthmakers for modal truths.
[src:denotation/actualism] For example, there is a possible world which is inhabited by purple cows.
[src:denotation/actualism] This world is a truthmaker for "there could have been purple cows".
[src:denotation/actualism] Cows are animals in all possible worlds that are inhabited by cows.
[src:denotation/actualism] So all worlds are the truthmaker of "it is necessary that all cows are animals".
[src:denotation/actualism] This account relies heavily on a logical notion of modality, since possibility and necessity are defined in terms of consistency.
[src:denotation/actualism] This dependency has prompted some philosophers to assert that no truthmakers at all are needed for modal truths, that modal truths are true "by default".
[src:denotation/actualism] This position involves abandoning truthmaker maximalism.
[src:denotation/actualism] An alternative solution to the problem of truthmakers for modal truths is based on the notion of essence.
[src:denotation/actualism] Objects have their properties either essentially or accidentally.
[src:denotation/actualism] The essence of an object involves all the properties it has essentially; it defines the object's nature: what it fundamentally is.
[src:denotation/actualism] On this type of account, the truthmaker for "it is necessary that all cows are animals" is that it belongs to the essence of cows to be animals.
[src:denotation/actualism] The truthmaker for "there could have been purple cows" is that color is not essential to cows.
[src:denotation/actualism] Some essentialist theories focus on object essences, i.e. that certain properties are essential to a specific object.
[src:denotation/actualism] Other essentialist theories focus on kind essences, i.e. that certain properties are essential to the kind or species of the object in question.
[src:denotation/actualism] Another account attempts to ground modal truths in the dispositions or powers of actually existing entities.
[src:denotation/actualism] So, for example, the claim that "it's possible that the teacup breaks" has its truthmaker in the teacup's disposition to break, i.e. in its fragility.
[src:denotation/actualism] While this type of theory can account for various truths, it has been questioned whether it can account for all truths.
[src:denotation/actualism] Problematic cases include truths like "it's possible that nothing existed" or "it's possible that the laws of nature had been different".
[src:denotation/actualism] A theistic version of this account has been proposed in order to solve these problems: God's power is the truthmaker for modal truths.
[src:denotation/actualism] "There could have been purple cows" because it was in God's power to create purple cows, while "it is necessary that all cows are animals" because it was not in God's power to create cows that are not animals.
[src:denotation/actualism] These solutions proposed on behalf of actualism can be divided into two categories: **Softcore actualism** and **hardcore actualism**.
[src:denotation/actualism] The adherents of these positions disagree on which part of the actual world is the foundation supporting modal truths.
[src:denotation/actualism] *Softcore actualists* hold that modal truths are grounded in the abstract realm, for example in possible worlds conceived as abstract objects existing in the actual world.
[src:denotation/actualism] *Hardcore actualists*, on the other hand, assert that modal truths are grounded in the concrete constituents of the actual world, for example in essences or in dispositions.
[src:denotation/actualism] According to the indexical conception of actuality, favoured by Lewis (1986), actuality is an attribute which our world has relative to itself, but which all the other worlds have relative to themselves too.
[src:denotation/actualism] Actuality is an intrinsic property of each world, so world *w* is actual just at world *w*.
[src:denotation/actualism] "Actual" is seen as an indexical term, and its reference depends on its context.
[src:denotation/actualism] Therefore, there is no feature of this world (nor of any other) to be distinguished in order to infer that the world is actual, "the actual world" is actual simply in virtue of the definition of "actual": a world is actual *simpliciter*.
[src:denotation/actualism] For example, assume that Gifre has the choice between two alternatives, eating a cookie or not eating anything.
[src:denotation/actualism] Having eaten the first cookie, Gifre could stop eating cookies, which is the best alternative.
[src:denotation/actualism] But after having tasted one cookie, Gifre would freely decide to continue eating cookies until the whole bag is finished, which would result in a terrible stomach ache and would be the worst alternative.
[src:denotation/actualism] Not eating any cookies at all, on the other hand, would be the second-best alternative.
[src:denotation/actualism] Now the question is: should Gifre eat the first cookie or not?
[src:denotation/actualism] Actualists are only concerned with the actual consequences.
[src:denotation/actualism] According to them, Gifre should not eat any cookies at all since it is better than the alternative leading to a stomach ache.
[src:denotation/actualism] Possibilists contend that the best possible course of action involves eating the first cookie and this is therefore what Gifre should do.
[src:denotation/actualism] One counterintuitive consequence of actualism is that agents can avoid moral obligations simply by having an imperfect moral character.
[src:denotation/actualism] For example, a lazy person might justify rejecting a request to help a friend by arguing that, due to her lazy character, she wouldn't have done the work anyway, even if she had accepted the request.
[src:denotation/actualism] By rejecting the offer right away, she managed at least not to waste anyone's time.
[src:denotation/actualism] Actualists might even consider her behavior praiseworthy since she did what, according to actualism, she ought to have done.
[src:denotation/actualism] This seems to be a very easy way to "get off the hook" that is avoided by possibilism.
[src:denotation/actualism] But possibilism has to face the objection that in some cases it sanctions and even recommends what actually leads to the worst outcome.
[src:denotation/actualism] Portmore has suggested that these and other problems of actualism and possibilism can be avoided by constraining what counts as a genuine alternative for the agent.
[src:denotation/actualism] On his view, it is a requirement that the agent has rational control over the event in question.
[src:denotation/actualism] For example, eating only one cookie and stopping afterward only is an option for Gifre if she has the rational capacity to repress her temptation to continue eating.
[src:denotation/actualism] If the temptation is irrepressible then this course of action is not considered to be an option and is therefore not relevant when assessing what the best alternative is.
[src:denotation/actualism] Portmore suggests that, given this adjustment, we should prefer a view very closely associated with *possibilism* called *maximalism*.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] Being Jewish, Adolf Grünbaum's family left Nazi Germany in 1938 and emigrated to the United States.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] Grünbaum received a B.A. with twofold High Distinction in philosophy and in mathematics from Wesleyan University, Middletown, Connecticut, in 1943.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] During the Second World War, Grünbaum was trained at Camp Ritchie, Maryland, and thus was one of the Ritchie Boys.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] He was stationed in Berlin and interrogated highly placed Nazis, returning to the United States in 1946.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] Grünbaum obtained both his M.S. in physics (1948) and his PhD in philosophy (1951) from Yale University.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] He was a chaired professor of philosophy at Lehigh University, Bethlehem, Pennsylvania (1956–1960), after rising through the ranks there, starting in 1950, becoming a full professor in 1955.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] In the fall of 1960, Grünbaum left Lehigh University to join the faculty of the University of Pittsburgh, where he became the first Andrew Mellon Professor of Philosophy.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] In that year, he also became the founding director of that University's Center for Philosophy of Science, serving as director until 1978.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] He and the colleagues he recruited then built world-class philosophy and history and philosophy of science departments at the university.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] Several of these colleagues had come from Yale University's philosophy department, starting in 1962.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] During this recruitment period the University of Pittsburgh appointed Nicholas Rescher, Wilfrid Sellars, Richard Gale, Nuel Belnap, Alan Ross Anderson, and Gerald Massey, among others.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] Grünbaum served as president of both the American Philosophical Association (Eastern Division) and the Philosophy of Science Association (two terms).
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] He was the director of the Center for Philosophy of Science from 1960 to 1978.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] He was the president of the Division of Logic, Methodology and Philosophy of Science of the International Union of History and Philosophy of Science (IUHPS) in 2004–2005 and then automatically became president of the IUHPS from 2006 to 2007.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] Scientist Prize from the Alexander von Humboldt Foundation (Germany, 1985), the Fregene Prize for science from the Italian Parliament (1998) and the Wilbur Lucius Cross Medal for outstanding achievement from Yale University (1990).
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] Also, in May 1995, he received an honorary doctorate from the University of Konstanz in Germany.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] In 2013, he received an honorary doctorate of philosophy from the University of Cologne and the Großes Bundesverdienstkreuz from the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] In April 2013 Grünbaum resigned from the department of philosophy at the University of Pittsburgh, while retaining his lifetime tenured Mellon Chair and all of his other affiliations at that university.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] He died in November 2018 at the age of 95.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] Grünbaum was the author of nearly 400 articles and book chapters as well as books on space-time and the critique of psychoanalysis.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] He is often viewed as part of the American brand of logical empiricism, associated especially with Hans Reichenbach.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] Grünbaum did not embrace the prevailing — especially among physical scientists — Popperian philosophy of science, leading to some notoriety in the 1960s after he was ridiculed in print by the physicist Richard Feynman.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] A much-quoted exchange followed Grünbaum's neo-Leibnizian suggestion that the flow of time might be an illusion only in conscious entities, in which Feynman asked whether dogs, then cockroaches, were sufficiently conscious entities.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] Reportedly as a mark of further disdain, Feynman refused to let his name be printed, becoming instead the easily recognizable "Mr.
[src:denotation/adolf-grünbaum] For more complete publication details see the Full Bibliography of Prof.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Alasdair Chalmers MacIntyre was born on 12 January 1929 in Glasgow, to Eneas and Greta (Chalmers) MacIntyre.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] He was educated at Queen Mary College, London, and had a Master of Arts degree from the University of Manchester, where his philosophy teacher was Dorothy Emmet and his fellow student was Herbert McCabe and from the University of Oxford.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] He began his teaching career in 1951 at Manchester.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] He married Ann Peri, with whom he had two daughters, Jean and Toni.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] He taught at the University of Leeds, the University of Essex and the University of Oxford in the United Kingdom, before moving to the US in around 1969.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] MacIntyre was something of an intellectual nomad, having taught at many universities in the US.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] He had also been a visiting professor at Princeton University and was president of the American Philosophical Association.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] In 2010, he was awarded the Aquinas Medal by the American Catholic Philosophical Association.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] He was a member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences (elected 1985), the British Academy (1994), the Royal Irish Academy (1999), and the American Philosophical Society (2005).
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] O'Brien Senior Research Professor in the Department of Philosophy (emeritus since 2010) at the University of Notre Dame, Indiana, US.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] He was also professor emerit and emeritus at Duke University.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] In July 2010, he became senior research fellow at London Metropolitan University's Centre for Contemporary Aristotelian Studies in Ethics and Politics.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] After his retirement from active teaching in 2010, MacIntyre remained the senior distinguished research fellow of the Notre Dame de Nicola Center for Ethics and Culture, where he retained an office.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] He continued to make public presentations, including an annual keynote as part of the de Nicola Center for Ethics and Culture's Fall Conference.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] From 1953 to 1963, he was married to Ann Peri, with whom he had two daughters.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] From 1963 to 1977, he was married to former teacher and now poet Susan Willans, with whom he had a son and daughter.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] From 1977 to his death, he was married to philosopher Lynn Joy, who is also on the philosophy faculty at Notre Dame.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] MacIntyre died on 21 May 2025 at a care facility in South Bend, Indiana, at the age of 96.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] MacIntyre's approach to moral philosophy interweaves a number of complex strands.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Although he largely aims to revive an Aristotelian moral philosophy based on the virtues, he claims a "peculiarly modern understanding" of this task.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] This "peculiarly modern understanding" largely concerns MacIntyre's approach to moral disputes.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Unlike some analytic philosophers who try to generate moral consensus on the basis of rationality, MacIntyre uses the historical development of ethics to circumvent the modern problem of "incommensurable" moral notions, whose merits cannot be compared in any common framework.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] He emphasizes how this overestimation of reason led to Nietzsche's utter repudiation of the possibility of moral rationality.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] He revives the tradition of Aristotelian ethics with its teleological account of the good and of moral actions, as fulfilled in the medieval writings of Thomas Aquinas.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] MacIntyre himself recalls some factors that led him to this Thomistic shift.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] American theologian Stanley Hauerwas is even more certain of this philosophical debt.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] He wrote, "the change in McIntyre's views of Aquinas' significance from *After Virtue* to *Whose Justice?
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Which Rationality?* no doubt is due to many factors, but surely Alasdair's regard for Herbert's reading of Aquinas had some effect".
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] This Aristotelian-Thomistic tradition, he proposes, presents "the best theory so far," both of how things are and how we ought to act.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] More generally, according to MacIntyre, moral disputes always take place within and between rival traditions of thought relying on an inherited store of ideas, presuppositions, types of arguments and shared understandings and approaches.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Even though there is no definitive way for one tradition in moral philosophy to logically refute another, nevertheless opposing views can dispute each other's internal coherence, resolution of imaginative dilemmas and epistemic crises, and achievement of fruitful results.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Probably his most widely read work, *After Virtue* was written when MacIntyre was already in his fifties.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] In general terms, the task of *After Virtue* is to account both for the dysfunction of modern moral discourse in modern society and to rehabilitate the alternative that is teleological rationality in Aristotelian virtue ethics.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] MacIntyre's philippic articulates a politics of self-defence for local communities who aspire to protect their traditional way of life from corrosive modern influences.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] MacIntyre's second major work of his mature period takes up the problem of giving an account of philosophical rationality within the context of his notion of "traditions," which had still remained under-theorized in *After Virtue*.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Specifically, MacIntyre argues that rival and largely incompatible conceptions of justice are the outcome of rival and largely incompatible forms of practical rationality.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Which Rationality?* is therefore engaged in the task of not only giving the reader examples of what MacIntyre considers actual rival traditions and the different ways they can split apart, integrate, or defeat one another (e.g.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Aristotelian, Augustinianism, Thomist, Humean) but also with substantiating how practical rationality and a conception of justice help constitute those traditions.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Specifically, according to him, the differing accounts of justice that are presented by Aristotle and Hume are due to the underlying differences in their conceptual schemes.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] MacIntyre's book ultimately conducts a complex series of both interior and exterior critiques of the encyclopaedic and genealogical positions in an attempt to vindicate philosophical Thomism as the most persuasive form of moral inquiry currently on offer.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] His critique in chapter IX of Nietzsche's and Michel Foucault's genealogical mode as implicitly committed to an emancipatory and continuous notion of self which they cannot account for on their own terms has been of particular influence.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] To advance rational inquiry, MacIntyre argues that lectures ought to take account of the tradition-constituted roles both of lecturer and of student.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Lecturers as members of explicitly articulated traditions should engage students, recognized as standing in various relationships to the lecturer's own and/or rival traditions, on material situated in the historically contextualised progress of the lecturer's home tradition.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] In support of such lectures and of tradition-bound inquiry on the research front, universities should become forums for growing and engaging rival traditions.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] For students, such forums would invite intentional formation within a tradition, and support learning how to profitably confront rival traditions through imaginative participation in them.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] For researchers, inquiry at the frontier must advance toward holistic, inter-disciplinary accounts, at once both theoretical and practical, undertaken together by members of communities of practitioners bound together in traditions.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Such tradition-bound inquiry contributes to the advancement of researchers' host traditions on their own terms.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Moreover, undertaking such inquiry in a reformed university setting would support encounters among host traditions and their rivals, and thus visibility as traditions both to themselves and to others through imaginative engagement with rival perspectives.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Engaging with scientific texts on human biology as well as works of philosophical anthropology, MacIntyre identifies the human species as existing on a continuous scale of both intelligence and dependency with other animals such as dolphins.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] One of his main goals is to undermine what he sees as the fiction of the disembodied, independent reasoner who determines ethical and moral questions autonomously and what he calls the "illusion of self-sufficiency" that runs through much of Western ethics culminating in Nietzsche's *Übermensch*.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] MacIntyre is a key figure in the recent surge of interest in virtue ethics, which identifies the central question of morality as having to do with the habits and knowledge concerning how to live a good life.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] His approach seeks to demonstrate that good judgment emanates from good character.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Being a good person is not about seeking to follow formal rules.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] In elaborating this approach, MacIntyre understands himself to be reworking the Aristotelian idea of an ethical teleology.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Before its recent resurgence, virtue ethics in European/American academia had been primarily associated with pre-modern philosophers (e.g.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] MacIntyre has argued that Aquinas' synthesis of Augustinianism with Aristotelianism is more insightful than modern moral theories by focusing upon the telos ('end', or completion) of social practice and of human life, within the context of which the morality of acts may be evaluated.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] His seminal work in the area of virtue ethics can be found in his 1981 book, *After Virtue*.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] MacIntyre intends the idea of virtue to supplement, rather than replace, moral rules.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Indeed, he describes certain moral rules as 'exceptionless' or unconditional.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] MacIntyre considers his work to be outside "virtue ethics" due to his affirmation of virtues as embedded in specific, historically grounded, social practices.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] Politically, MacIntyre's ethics informs a defence of the Aristotelian 'goods of excellence' internal to practices against the modern pursuit of 'external goods', such as money, power, and status, that are characteristic of rule-based, utilitarian, Weberian modern institutions.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] He has been described as a 'revolutionary Aristotelian' because he attempted to combine historical insights from his Marxist past with those of Thomas Aquinas and Aristotle after MacIntyre's conversion to Catholicism.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] For him, liberalism and postmodern consumerism not only justify capitalism but also sustain and inform it over the long term.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] At the same time, he says that "Marxists have always fallen back into relatively straightforward versions of Kantianism or utilitarianism" (*After Virtue*, p.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] 261) and criticizes Marxism as just another form of radical individualism.
[src:denotation/alasdair-macintyre] In 1951 in student debates at Manchester, MacIntyre described himself as a Disraeli Tory but later was a member of the Communist Party of Great Britain (leaving in 1956), briefly of the Socialist Labour League, and later of the Socialist Review Group/International Socialists.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] His best known book is *The Principle of Sufficient Reason: A Reassessment* (2006).
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] He is also the author of the books, *Actuality, Possibility and Worlds* (2011), and *One Body: An Essay in Christian Sexual Ethics* (2012), and a number of academic papers on religion and theology.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] He maintains his own philosophy blog and contributed to the Prosblogion philosophy of religion blog.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] Alexander Pruss first lived in Poland, but emigrated to Canada.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] He went to the University of Western Ontario, studying physics and mathematics and graduating with a B.Sc. in these fields in 1991.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] He earned a Ph.D. in mathematics at the University of British Columbia with a dissertation on *Symmetrization, Green’s Functions, Harmonic Measures and Difference Equations*, under John J.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] Fournier in 1996, and published several papers in *Proceedings of the American Mathematical Society* and other mathematical journals.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] Afterwards, he began graduate work in philosophy at the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] He completed his dissertation, *Possible Worlds: What They Are and What They Are Good For*, under Nicholas Rescher in 2001.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] Pruss began teaching philosophy at Georgetown University in 2001, earning tenure in 2006.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] In 2007, he began to teach philosophy at Baylor University.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] He is now the director of graduate studies for the Baylor Philosophy Department.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] He has taught various courses, including graduate seminars on the philosophy of time, metaphysics, the cosmological and ontological arguments for the existence of God, modality, free will, and history of philosophy.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] Pruss's philosophical thought reflects Christian orthodoxy.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] He is a Roman Catholic and a member of the Society of Christian Philosophers.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] Pruss defends the principle of sufficient reason (PSR), claiming that it is self-evident, and arguing that the rejection of PSR creates problems in epistemology, modality, ethics, and even evolutionary theory.
[src:denotation/alexander-pruss] Pruss is a critic of David Lewis's "extreme modal realism," and instead gives "a combined account" of Leibnizian and Aristotelian modality, which integrates the "this-worldly capacities" of the Aristotelian view and Leibniz's account of possible worlds as thoughts in the mind of God.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In his early career Whitehead wrote primarily on mathematics, logic, and physics.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He wrote the three-volume *Principia Mathematica* (1910–1913), with his former student Bertrand Russell.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] *Principia Mathematica* is considered one of the twentieth century's most important works in mathematical logic, and placed 23rd in a list of the top 100 English-language nonfiction books of the twentieth century by Modern Library.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Beginning in the late 1910s and early 1920s, Whitehead gradually turned his attention from mathematics to philosophy of science, and finally to metaphysics.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He developed a comprehensive metaphysical system which radically departed from most of Western philosophy.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead argued that reality consists of processes rather than material objects, and that processes are best defined by their relations with other processes, thus rejecting the theory that reality is fundamentally constructed by bits of matter that exist independently of one another.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's philosophical works – particularly *Process and Reality* – are regarded as the foundational texts of process philosophy.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Alfred North Whitehead was born in Ramsgate, Kent, England, in 1861.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] His father, Alfred Whitehead, became an Anglican minister after being headmaster of Chatham House Academy, a school for boys previously headed by Alfred's father, Thomas Whitehead.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead himself recalled both of them as being very successful schoolmasters, with his grandfather being the more "remarkable" man.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's mother was Maria Sarah Buckmaster.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Her maternal great-grandmother was Jane North (1776–1847), whose maiden surname was given to Whitehead, and several other members of his family over time.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] His mother, Maria Buckmaster had eleven siblings.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The son of her brother Thomas, Walter Selby Buckmaster, was twice an Olympics silver medal winner for Polo (1900, 1908) for Britain, and is said to be "one of the finest polo players England has ever produced".
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead does not appear to have been close to his mother, although he and Evelyn (full name: Evelyn Ada Maud Rice Willoughby Wade), whom he married in 1890, are recorded in the English Census of 1891 as living with Alfred's mother and father.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Lowe notes that there appears to have been mutual dislike between Whitehead's wife, Evelyn, and his mother, Maria.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Griffin relates how Bertrand Russell, a colleague and collaborator of Whitehead, was a very close friend of Whitehead and of his wife, Evelyn.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Intensity of emotion was encouraged by their avant-garde associates in the turbulent Bloomsbury Group which "discussed aesthetic and philosophical questions in a spirit of agnosticism and were strongly influenced by G.E.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Moore's *Principia Ethica* (1903) and by A.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's and Bertrand Russell's *Principia Mathematica* (1910–13), in the light of which they searched for definitions of the good, the true, and the beautiful".
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Alfred's brother Henry became Bishop of Madras and wrote the closely observed ethnographic account *Village Gods of South-India* (Calcutta: Association Press, 1921).
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead was educated at Sherborne, a prominent English public school, where he excelled in sports and mathematics and was head prefect of his class.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1880, he began attending Trinity College, Cambridge, and studied mathematics.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He earned his B.A. from Trinity in 1884, writing his dissertation on James Clerk Maxwell's *A Treatise on Electricity and Magnetism*, and graduated as fourth wrangler.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1910, Whitehead resigned his senior lectureship in mathematics at Trinity and moved to London without first obtaining another job.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] After being unemployed for a year, he accepted a position as lecturer in applied mathematics and mechanics at University College London but was passed over a year later for the Goldsmid Chair of Applied Mathematics and Mechanics, a position for which he had hoped to be seriously considered.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1914, Whitehead accepted a position as professor of applied mathematics at the newly chartered Imperial College London, where his old friend Andrew Forsyth had recently been appointed chief professor of mathematics.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1918, Whitehead's academic responsibilities began to seriously expand as he accepted a number of high administrative positions within the University of London system (of which Imperial College London was a member at the time).
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead was able to exert his newfound influence to successfully lobby for a new history of science department, help establish a Bachelor of Science degree (previously only Bachelor of Arts degrees had been offered), and make the school more accessible to less wealthy students.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Toward the end of his time in England, Whitehead turned his attention to philosophy.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Though he had no advanced training in philosophy, his philosophical work soon became highly regarded.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] After publishing *The Concept of Nature* in 1920, he served as president of the Aristotelian Society from 1922 to 1923.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1924, Henry Osborn Taylor invited the 63-year-old Whitehead to join the faculty at Harvard University as a professor of philosophy.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The Whiteheads would spend the rest of their lives in the United States.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] During his time at Harvard, Whitehead produced some of his most important philosophical contributions.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1925, he wrote *Science and the Modern World*, which was immediately hailed as an alternative to the Cartesian dualism then prevalent in popular science.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences that same year.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1926.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Lectures from 1927 to 1928 were published in 1929 as a book named *Process and Reality*, which has been compared to Immanuel Kant's *Critique of Pure Reason*.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1890, Whitehead married Evelyn Wade, an Irishwoman raised in France; they had a daughter, Jessie, and two sons, Thomas and Eric.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Thomas followed his father to Harvard in 1931, to teach at the Business School.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Eric died in action at the age of 19, while serving in the Royal Flying Corps during World War I.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] From 1910, the Whiteheads had a cottage in the village of Lockeridge, near Marlborough, Wiltshire; from there he completed *Principia Mathematica*.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The Whiteheads remained in the United States after moving to Harvard in 1924.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Alfred retired from Harvard in 1937 and remained in Cambridge, Massachusetts, until his death on 30 December 1947.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The two-volume biography of Whitehead by Victor Lowe is the most definitive presentation of the life of Whitehead.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] However, many details of Whitehead's life remain obscure because he left no *Nachlass* (personal archive); his family carried out his instructions that all of his papers be destroyed after his death.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Additionally, Whitehead was known for his "almost fanatical belief in the right to privacy," and for writing very few personal letters of the kind that would help to gain insight on his life.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Lucas Jr., the Whitehead Research Project of the Center for Process Studies is currently working on a critical edition of Whitehead's published and unpublished works.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The first volume of the *Edinburgh Critical Edition of the Complete Works of Alfred North Whitehead* was published in 2017 by Paul A.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Bogaard and Jason Bell as *The Harvard Lectures of Alfred North Whitehead, 1924–1925: The Philosophical Presuppositions of Science*.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In addition to numerous articles on mathematics, Whitehead wrote three major books on the subject: *A Treatise on Universal Algebra* (1898), *Principia Mathematica* (co-written with Bertrand Russell and published in three volumes between 1910 and 1913), and *An Introduction to Mathematics* (1911).
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The former two books were aimed exclusively at professional mathematicians, while the latter book was intended for a larger audience, covering the history of mathematics and its philosophical foundations.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] *Principia Mathematica* in particular is regarded as one of the most important works in mathematical logic of the 20th century.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In *A Treatise on Universal Algebra* (1898), the term *universal algebra* had essentially the same meaning that it has today: the study of algebraic structures themselves, rather than examples ("models") of algebraic structures.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead credits William Rowan Hamilton and Augustus De Morgan as originators of the subject matter, and James Joseph Sylvester with coining the term itself.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] At the time, structures such as Lie algebras and hyperbolic quaternions drew attention to the need to expand algebraic structures beyond the associatively multiplicative class.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In a review Alexander Macfarlane wrote: "The main idea of the work is not unification of the several methods, nor generalization of ordinary algebra so as to include them, but rather the comparative study of their several structures." In a separate review, G.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead, however, had no results of a general nature.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] His hope of "form[ing] a uniform method of interpretation of the various algebras" presumably would have been developed in Volume II, had Whitehead completed it.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Further work on the subject was minimal until the early 1930s when Garrett Birkhoff and Øystein Ore began publishing on universal algebras.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead and Russell had thought originally that *Principia Mathematica* would take a year to complete; it ended up taking them ten years.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Despite the initial loss, today there is likely no major academic library in the world that does not hold a copy of *Principia Mathematica*.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Unlike Whitehead's previous two books on mathematics, *An Introduction to Mathematics* (1911) was not aimed exclusively at professional mathematicians but was intended for a larger audience.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The book covered the nature of mathematics, its unity and internal structure, and its applicability to nature.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The book can be seen as an attempt to understand the growth in unity and interconnection of mathematics as a whole, as well as an examination of the mutual influence of mathematics and philosophy, language, and physics.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Although the book is little-read, in some ways it prefigures certain points of Whitehead's later work in philosophy and metaphysics.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead showed a deep concern for educational reform at all levels.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In addition to his numerous individually written works on the subject, Whitehead was appointed by Britain's Prime Minister David Lloyd George as part of a 20-person committee to investigate the educational systems and practices of the UK in 1921 and recommend reform.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's most complete work on education is the 1929 book *The Aims of Education and Other Essays*, which collected numerous essays and addresses by Whitehead on the subject published between 1912 and 1927.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The essay from which *Aims of Education* derived its name was delivered as an address in 1916 when Whitehead was president of the London Branch of the Mathematical Association.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In it, he cautioned against the teaching of what he called "inert ideas" – ideas that are disconnected scraps of information, with no application to real life or culture.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Rather than teach small parts of a large number of subjects, Whitehead advocated teaching a relatively few important concepts that the student could organically link to many different areas of knowledge, discovering their application in actual life.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In order to make this sort of teaching a reality, however, Whitehead pointed to the need to minimize the importance of (or radically alter) standard examinations for school entrance.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead argued that curriculum should be developed specifically for its own students by its own staff, or else risk total stagnation, interrupted only by occasional movements from one group of inert ideas to another.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Above all else in his educational writings, Whitehead emphasized the importance of imagination and the free play of ideas.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's philosophy of education might adequately be summarized in his statement that "knowledge does not keep any better than fish".
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In other words, bits of disconnected knowledge are meaningless; all knowledge must find some imaginative application to the students' own lives, or else it becomes useless trivia, and the students themselves become good at parroting facts but not thinking for themselves.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead did not begin his career as a philosopher.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In fact, he never had any formal training in philosophy beyond his undergraduate education.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Early in his life, he showed great interest in and respect for philosophy and metaphysics, but it is evident that he considered himself a rank amateur.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] However, interest in metaphysics – the philosophical investigation of the nature of the universe and existence – had become unfashionable by the time Whitehead began writing in earnest about it in the 1920s.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The ever-more impressive accomplishments of empirical science had led to a general consensus in academia that the development of comprehensive metaphysical systems was a waste of time because they were not subject to empirical testing.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead was unimpressed by this objection.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In the notes of one of his students for a 1927 class, Whitehead was quoted as saying: "Every scientific man in order to preserve his reputation has to say he dislikes metaphysics.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] What he means is he dislikes having his metaphysics criticized." In Whitehead's view, scientists and philosophers make metaphysical assumptions about how the universe works all the time, but such assumptions are not easily seen precisely because they remain unexamined and unquestioned.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For this reason, Whitehead regarded metaphysical investigations as essential to both good science and good philosophy.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He also argued that the most basic elements of reality can all be regarded as experiential, indeed that everything is constituted by its experience.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He used the term "experience" very broadly so that even inanimate processes such as electron collisions are said to manifest some degree of experience.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In this, he went against Descartes' separation of two different kinds of real existence, either exclusively material or else exclusively mental.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's philosophy was highly original, and soon garnered interest in philosophical circles.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] This is not to say that Whitehead's thought was widely accepted or even well understood.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] His philosophical work is generally considered to be among the most difficult to understand in all of the Western canon.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Even professional philosophers struggled to follow Whitehead's writings.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] It may not be inappropriate to speculate that some fair portion of the respect generally shown to Whitehead by his philosophical peers at the time arose from their sheer bafflement.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] However, Mathews' frustration with Whitehead's books did not negatively affect his interest.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In fact, there were numerous philosophers and theologians at Chicago's Divinity School who perceived the importance of what Whitehead was doing without fully grasping all of the details and implications.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1927, they invited one of America's only Whitehead experts, Henry Nelson Wieman, to Chicago to give a lecture explaining Whitehead's thoughts.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Wieman's lecture was so brilliant that he was promptly hired to the faculty and taught there for twenty years, and for at least thirty years afterwards Chicago's Divinity School was closely associated with Whitehead's thought.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead was convinced that the scientific notion of matter was misleading as a way of describing the ultimate nature of things.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In Whitehead's view, there are a number of problems with this notion of "irreducible brute matter".
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] First, it obscures and minimizes the importance of change.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] By thinking of any material thing (like a rock, or a person) as being fundamentally the *same* thing throughout time, with any changes to it being secondary to its "nature", scientific materialism hides the fact that nothing ever stays the same.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For Whitehead, change is fundamental and inescapable; he emphasizes that "all things flow".
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In Whitehead's view, then, concepts such as "quality", "matter", and "form" are problematic.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] These "classical" concepts fail to adequately account for change, and overlook the active and experiential nature of the most basic elements of the world.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] They are useful abstractions but are not the world's basic building blocks.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] What is ordinarily conceived of as a single person, for instance, is philosophically described as a continuum of overlapping events.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] After all, people change all the time, if only because they have aged by another second and had some further experience.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] These occasions of experience are logically distinct but are progressively connected in what Whitehead calls a "society" of events.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] By assuming that enduring objects are the most real and fundamental things in the universe, materialists have mistaken the abstract for the concrete (what Whitehead calls the "fallacy of misplaced concreteness").
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] To put it another way, a thing or person is often seen as having a "defining essence" or a "core identity" that is unchanging, and describes what the thing or person *really is*.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In this way of thinking, things and people are seen as fundamentally the same through time, with any changes being qualitative and secondary to their core identity (e.g., "Mark's hair has turned grey as he has gotten older, but he is still the same person").
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] But in Whitehead's cosmology, the only fundamentally existent things are discrete "occasions of experience" that overlap one another in time and space, and jointly make up the enduring person or thing.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] On the other hand, what ordinary thinking often regards as "the essence of a thing" or "the identity/core of a person" is an abstract generalization of what is regarded as that person or thing's most important or salient features across time.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Identities do not define people; people define identities.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Everything changes from moment to moment and to think of anything as having an "enduring essence" misses the fact that "all things flow," though it is often a useful way of speaking.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead pointed to the limitations of language as one of the main culprits in maintaining a materialistic way of thinking and acknowledged that it may be difficult to ever wholly move past such ideas in everyday speech.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Yet the limitations of everyday living and everyday speech should not prevent people from realizing that "material substances" or "essences" are a convenient generalized description of a continuum of particular, concrete processes.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] No one questions that a ten-year-old person is quite different by the time he or she turns thirty years old, and in many ways is not the same person at all; Whitehead points out that it is not philosophically or ontologically sound to think that a person is the same from one second to the next.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] A second problem with materialism is that it obscures the importance of *relations*.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] It sees every object as distinct and discrete from all other objects.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Each object is simply an inert clump of matter that is only *externally* related to other things.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The idea of matter as primary makes people think of objects as being fundamentally separate in time and space, and not necessarily related to anything.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] But in Whitehead's view, relations take a primary role, perhaps even more important than the relata themselves.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] A student taking notes in one of Whitehead's fall 1924 classes wrote that, "Reality applies to *connections*, and only relatively to the things connected.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] A real thing is just that which forces the rest of the universe to in some way conform to it; that is to say, if theoretically, a thing made strictly no difference to any other entity (i.e., it was not *related* to any other entity), it could not be said to really exist.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Relations are not secondary to what a thing is; they *are* what the thing is.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] To Whitehead, an entity is not *merely* a sum of its relations, but also a valuation of them and reaction to them.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For Whitehead, creativity is the absolute principle of existence, and every entity (whether it is a human being, a tree, or an electron) has some degree of novelty in how it responds to other entities and is not fully determined by causal or mechanistic laws.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Most entities do not have consciousness.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] As a human being's actions cannot always be predicted, the same can be said of where a tree's roots will grow, or how an electron will move, or whether it will rain tomorrow.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Moreover, the inability to predict an electron's movement (for instance) is not due to faulty understanding or inadequate technology; rather, the fundamental creativity/freedom of all entities means that there will always remain phenomena that are unpredictable.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The other side of creativity/freedom as the absolute principle is that every entity is constrained by the social structure of existence (i.e., its relations); each actual entity must conform to the settled conditions of the world around it.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] But an entity's uniqueness and individuality arise from its own self-determination as to just how it will take account of the world within the limits that have been set for it.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In summary, Whitehead rejects the idea of separate and unchanging bits of matter as the most basic building blocks of reality, in favour of the idea of reality as interrelated events in the process.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Since Whitehead's metaphysics described a universe in which all entities experience, he needed a new way of describing perception that was not limited to living, self-conscious beings.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The term he coined was "prehension," which comes from the Latin *prehensio*, meaning "to seize".
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The term is meant to indicate a kind of perception that can be conscious or unconscious, applying to people as well as electrons.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] It is also intended to make clear Whitehead's rejection of the theory of *representative* perception, in which the mind only has private ideas about other entities.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For Whitehead, the term "prehension" indicates that the perceiver actually incorporates aspects of the perceived thing into itself.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In this way, entities are constituted by their perceptions and relations, rather than being independent of them.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Further, Whitehead regards perception as occurring in two modes, *causal efficacy* (or "physical prehension") and *presentational immediacy* (or "conceptual prehension").
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Presentational immediacy, on the other hand, is what is usually referred to as "pure sense perception", unmediated by any causal or symbolic interpretation, even unconscious interpretation.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In other words, it is pure appearance, which may or may not be delusive (e.g., mistaking an image in a mirror for "the real thing").
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In higher organisms (like people), these two modes of perception combine into what Whitehead terms "symbolic reference", which links appearance with causation in a process that is so automatic that both people and animals have difficulty refraining from it.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] By way of illustration, Whitehead uses the example of a person's encounter with a chair.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] An ordinary person looks up, sees a coloured shape, and immediately infers that it is a chair.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead believed that when asking questions about the basic facts of existence, questions about value and purpose can never be fully escaped.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] This is borne out in his thoughts on abiogenesis, or the hypothetical natural process by which life arises from simple organic compounds.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In other words, Whitehead sees life as directed toward the purpose of increasing its own satisfaction.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Without such a goal, he sees the rise of life as totally unintelligible.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For Whitehead, there is no such thing as wholly inert matter.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Instead, all things have some measure of freedom or creativity, however small, which allows them to be at least partly self-directed.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The process philosopher David Ray Griffin coined the term "panexperientialism" (the idea that all entities experience) to describe Whitehead's view, and to distinguish it from panpsychism (the idea that all matter has consciousness).
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's idea of God differs from traditional monotheistic notions.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For Whitehead, God is not necessarily tied to religion.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Rather than springing primarily from religious faith, Whitehead saw God as necessary for his metaphysical system.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] His system required that an order exist among possibilities, an order that allowed for novelty in the world and provided an aim to all entities.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead posited that these ordered potentials exist in what he called the *primordial nature* of God.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] However, Whitehead was also interested in religious experience.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] This led him to reflect more intensively on what he saw as the second nature of God, the *consequent nature*.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's conception of God as a "dipolar" entity has called for fresh theological thinking.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The primordial nature he described as "the unlimited conceptual realization of the absolute wealth of potentiality" – i.e., the unlimited possibility of the universe.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] This primordial nature is eternal and unchanging, providing entities in the universe with possibilities for realization.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead also calls this primordial aspect "the lure for feeling, the eternal urge of desire," pulling the entities in the universe toward as-yet unrealized possibilities.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] God's consequent nature, on the other hand, is anything but unchanging; it is God's reception of the world's activity.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] As Whitehead puts it, "[God] saves the world as it passes into the immediacy of his own life.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] It is the judgment of a tenderness which loses nothing that can be saved." In other words, God saves and cherishes all experiences forever, and those experiences go on to change the way God interacts with the world.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In this way, God is really changed by what happens in the world and the wider universe, lending the actions of finite creatures an eternal significance.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead thus sees God and the world as fulfilling one another.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He sees entities in the world as fluent and changing things that yearn for a permanence which only God can provide by taking them into God's self, thereafter changing God and affecting the rest of the universe throughout time.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] On the other hand, he sees God as permanent but as deficient in actuality and change: alone, God is merely eternally unrealized possibilities and requires the world to actualize them.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] God gives creatures permanence, while the creatures give God actuality and change.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The above is some of Whitehead's most evocative writing about God, and was powerful enough to inspire the movement known as process theology, a vibrant theological school of thought that continues to thrive today.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For Whitehead, the core of religion was individual.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] While he acknowledged that individuals cannot ever be fully separated from their society, he argued that life is an internal fact for its own sake before it is an external fact relating to others.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] His most famous remark on religion is that "religion is what the individual does with his own solitariness ... and if you are never solitary, you are never religious." Whitehead saw religion as a system of general truths that transformed a person's character.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He took special care to note that while religion is often a good influence, it is not *necessarily* good – an idea which he called a "dangerous delusion" (e.g., a religion might encourage the violent extermination of a rival religion's adherents).
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] However, while Whitehead saw religion as *beginning* in solitariness, he also saw religion as necessarily expanding beyond the individual.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead writes further that each entity "can find no such value till it has merged its individual claim with that of the objective universe.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The spirit at once surrenders itself to this universal claim and appropriates it for itself." In this way, the individual and universal/social aspects of religion are mutually dependent.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] A connection between the works of William DeWitt Hyde and Whitehead further elucidates this necessary duality of social and individual roles in religious experience.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For Whitehead, religion served as a kind of bridge between philosophy and the emotions and purposes of a particular society.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] It is the task of religion to make philosophy applicable to the everyday lives of ordinary people.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] One of the first theologians to attempt to interact with Whitehead's thought was the future Archbishop of Canterbury, William Temple.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In Temple's Gifford Lectures of 1932–1934 (subsequently published as "Nature, Man and God"), Whitehead is one of a number of philosophers of the emergent evolution approach with which Temple interacts.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] However, it was not until the 1970s and 1980s that Whitehead's thought drew much attention outside of a small group of philosophers and theologians, primarily Americans, and even today he is not considered especially influential outside of relatively specialized circles.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Early followers of Whitehead were found primarily at the University of Chicago Divinity School, where Henry Nelson Wieman initiated an interest in Whitehead's work that would last for about thirty years.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Professors such as Wieman, Charles Hartshorne, Bernard Loomer, Bernard Meland, and Daniel Day Williams made Whitehead's philosophy arguably the most important intellectual thread running through the divinity school.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] They taught generations of Whitehead scholars, the most notable of whom is John B.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Although interest in Whitehead has since faded at Chicago's divinity school, Cobb effectively grabbed the torch and planted it firmly in Claremont, California, where he began teaching at Claremont School of Theology in 1958 and founded the Center for Process Studies with David Ray Griffin in 1973.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Largely due to Cobb's influence, today Claremont remains strongly identified with Whitehead's process thought.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] But while Claremont remains the most concentrated hub of Whiteheadian activity, the place where Whitehead's thought currently seems to be growing the most quickly is in China.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In order to address the challenges of modernization and industrialization, China has begun to blend traditions of Taoism, Buddhism, and Confucianism with Whitehead's "constructive post-modern" philosophy in order to create an "ecological civilization".
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] To date, the Chinese government has encouraged the building of twenty-three university-based centres for the study of Whitehead's philosophy, and books by process philosophers John Cobb and David Ray Griffin are becoming required reading for Chinese graduate students.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Cobb has attributed China's interest in process philosophy partly to Whitehead's stress on the mutual interdependence of humanity and nature, as well as his emphasis on an educational system that includes the teaching of values rather than simply bare facts.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Overall, however, Whitehead's influence is very difficult to characterize.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In English-speaking countries, his primary works are little-studied outside of Claremont and a select number of liberal graduate-level theology and philosophy programs.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Outside of these circles, his influence is relatively small and diffuse and has tended to come chiefly through the work of his students and admirers rather than Whitehead himself.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Deleuze's and Latour's opinions, however, are minority ones, as Whitehead has not been recognized as particularly influential within the most dominant philosophical schools.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Historically, Whitehead's work has been most influential in the field of American progressive theology.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] The most important early proponent of Whitehead's thought in a theological context was Charles Hartshorne, who spent a semester at Harvard as Whitehead's teaching assistant in 1925, and is widely credited with developing Whitehead's process philosophy into a full-blown process theology.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Other notable process theologians include John B.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Cobb, David Ray Griffin, Marjorie Hewitt Suchocki, C.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Robert Mesle, Roland Faber, and Catherine Keller.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Process theology typically stresses God's relational nature.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Rather than seeing God as impassive or emotionless, process theologians view God as "the fellow sufferer who understands," and as the being who is supremely affected by temporal events.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Hartshorne points out that people would not praise a human ruler who was unaffected by either the joys or sorrows of his followers – so why would this be a praiseworthy quality in God?
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Instead, as the being who is most affected by the world, God is the being who can most appropriately respond to the world.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] However, process theology has been formulated in a wide variety of ways.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Robert Mesle, for instance, advocates a "process naturalism" – i.e., a process theology without God.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In fact, process theology is difficult to define because process theologians are so diverse and transdisciplinary in their views and interests.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Cobb is a process theologian who has also written books on biology and economics.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Roland Faber and Catherine Keller integrate Whitehead with poststructuralist, postcolonialist, and feminist theory.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Charles Birch was both a theologian and a geneticist.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Gamwell writes on theology and political theory.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In *Syntheism – Creating God in The Internet Age*, futurologists Alexander Bard and Jan Söderqvist repeatedly credit Whitehead for the process theology they see rising out of the participatory culture expected to dominate the digital era.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Process philosophy is even more difficult to pin down than process theology.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In practice, the two fields cannot be neatly separated.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] One philosophical school which has historically had a close relationship with process philosophy is American pragmatism.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Whitehead himself thought highly of William James and John Dewey, and acknowledged his indebtedness to them in the preface to *Process and Reality*.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Charles Hartshorne (along with Paul Weiss) edited the collected papers of Charles Sanders Peirce, one of the founders of pragmatism.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Noted neopragmatist Richard Rorty was in turn a student of Hartshorne.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Scientists of the early 20th century for whom Whitehead's work has been influential include physical chemist Ilya Prigogine, biologist Conrad Hal Waddington, and geneticists Charles Birch and Sewall Wright.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Henry Murray dedicated his "Explorations in Personality" to Whitehead, a contemporary at Harvard.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In physics, Whitehead's theory of gravitation articulated a view that might perhaps be regarded as dual to Albert Einstein's general relativity.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Yutaka Tanaka suggested that the gravitational constant disagrees with experimental findings, and proposed that Einstein's work does not actually refute Whitehead's formulation.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Whitehead's view has now been rendered obsolete, with the discovery of gravitational waves, phenomena observed locally that largely violate the kind of local flatness of space that Whitehead assumes.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Consequently, Whitehead's cosmology must be regarded as a local approximation, and his assumption of a uniform spatio-temporal geometry, Minkowskian in particular, as an often-locally-adequate approximation.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] An exact replacement of Whitehead's cosmology would need to admit a Riemannian geometry.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Also, although Whitehead himself gave only secondary consideration to quantum theory, his metaphysics of processes has proved attractive to some physicists in that field.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Henry Stapp and David Bohm are among those whose work has been influenced by Whitehead.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In the 21st century, Whiteheadian thought is still a stimulating influence: Timothy E.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Henning, Adam Scarfe, and Dorion Sagan's *Beyond Mechanism* (2013) and Rupert Sheldrake's *Science Set Free* (2012) are examples of Whiteheadian approaches to biology.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] One of the most promising applications of Whitehead's thought in recent years has been in the area of ecological civilization, sustainability, and environmental ethics.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] A Theology of Ecology* (1971) was the first single-authored book on environmental ethics.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Whitehead is widely known for his influence in education theory.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] His philosophy inspired the formation of the Association for Process Philosophy of Education (APPE), which published eleven volumes of a journal titled *Process Papers* on process philosophy and education from 1996 to 2008.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Whitehead's theories on education also led to the formation of new modes of learning and new models of teaching.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] One such model is the ANISA model developed by Daniel C.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Jordan, which sought to address a lack of understanding of the nature of people in current education systems.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Another model is the FEELS model developed by Xie Bangxiu and deployed successfully in China.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] "FEELS" stands for five things in curriculum and education: Flexible-goals, Engaged-learner, Embodied-knowledge, Learning-through-interactions, and Supportive-teacher.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Whitehead's philosophy of education has also found institutional support in Canada, where the University of Saskatchewan created a Process Philosophy Research Unit and sponsored several conferences on process philosophy and education.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Howard Woodhouse at the University of Saskatchewan remains a strong proponent of Whiteheadian education.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] "Beyond the Modern University: Toward a Constructive Postmodern University," (2002) is another text that explores the importance of Whitehead's metaphysics for thinking about higher education.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Whitehead has had some influence on the philosophy of business administration and organizational theory.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] This has led in part to a focus on identifying and investigating the effect of temporal events (as opposed to static things) within organizations through an "organization studies" discourse that accommodates a variety of 'weak' and 'strong' process perspectives from a number of philosophers.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Staton have also written recently on the mutual influence of Whitehead and Mary Parker Follett, a pioneer in the fields of organizational theory and organizational behaviour.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Stout and Staton see both Whitehead and Follett as sharing an ontology that "understands becoming as a relational process; difference as being related, yet unique; and the purpose of becoming as harmonizing difference." This connection is further analyzed by Stout and Jeannine M.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Love in *Integrative Process: Follettian Thinking from Ontology to Administration*.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Whitehead's political views sometimes appear to be libertarian without the label.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] On the other hand, many Whitehead scholars read his work as providing a philosophical foundation for the social liberalism of the New Liberal movement that was prominent throughout Whitehead's adult life.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Morris wrote that "... there is good reason for claiming that Whitehead shared the social and political ideals of the new liberals.".
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] However, Whitehead's comment addresses means and methods, not "ideals" or pretexts or excuses.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Books written by Whitehead, listed by date of publication.
[src:denotation/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In addition, the Whitehead Research Project of the Center for Process Studies is currently working on a critical edition of Whitehead's writings, which is set to include notes taken by Whitehead's students during his Harvard classes, correspondence, and corrected editions of his books.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Educated in Poland at the University of Warsaw, and a member of the Lwów–Warsaw school of logic and the Warsaw school of mathematics, in 1939 he immigrated to the United States, where in 1945 he became a naturalized citizen.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski taught and carried out research in mathematics at the University of California, Berkeley, from 1942 until his death in 1983.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Alfred Tarski was born Alfred Teitelbaum (Polish spelling: "Tajtelbaum") to Polish-Jewish parents in comfortable circumstances.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] He first showed mathematical ability in secondary school, at Warsaw's *Szkoła Mazowiecka*.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Nevertheless, in 1918 he entered the University of Warsaw intending to study biology.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] After Poland regained independence in 1918, Warsaw University came under the leadership of Jan Łukasiewicz, Stanisław Leśniewski, and Wacław Sierpiński and quickly became a world-leading research institution in logic, foundational mathematics, and the philosophy of mathematics.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Leśniewski recognized Tarski's potential as a mathematician and encouraged him to abandon biology.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski attended courses taught by Łukasiewicz, Sierpiński, Stefan Mazurkiewicz, and Tadeusz Kotarbiński and in 1924 became the only person ever to complete a doctorate under Leśniewski's supervision.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] His thesis, *O wyrazie pierwotnym logistyki* (*On the Primitive Term of Logistic*), was published in 1923.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski and Leśniewski soon grew cool to each other, mainly due to Leśniewski's growing anti-semitism.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In later life, however, Tarski expressed the warmest praise (which was reciprocated) for Kotarbiński.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In 1923, Alfred Teitelbaum and his brother Wacław changed their surname to “Tarski”.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] The brothers also converted to Roman Catholicism, Poland's dominant religion, even though Alfred was an avowed atheist.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] After becoming the youngest person ever to complete a doctorate at Warsaw University, Tarski taught logic at the Polish Pedagogical Institute, mathematics and logic at the university, and served as Łukasiewicz's assistant.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Because these positions were poorly paid, from 1925 Tarski also taught mathematics at the Third Boys’ Gymnasium (seondary school) of the Trade Union of Polish Secondary-School Teachers (later the Stefan Żeromski Gymnasium).
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Before World War II it was not uncommon for European intellectuals of research caliber to teach secondary school.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Until his departure for the United States in 1939, Tarski wrote several textbooks and many papers – a number of them ground-breaking – while supporting himself mainly by teaching secondary-school mathematics.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In 1929 Tarski married fellow teacher Maria Witkowska, a Catholic Pole who had served during the Polish–Soviet War (1919–1921) as a courier for the Polish Army.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] They had two children: son Jan Tarski, who became a physicist; and daughter Ina, who married mathematician Andrzej Ehrenfeucht.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski applied for a chair of philosophy at Lwów University, but on Bertrand Russell's recommendation it was awarded to Leon Chwistek.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In 1930 Tarski visited the University of Vienna, lectured to Karl Menger's colloquium, and met Kurt Gödel.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Thanks to a fellowship, he was able to return to Vienna during the first half of 1935 to work with Menger's research group.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] From Vienna he traveled to Paris to present his ideas on truth at the first meeting of the Unity of Science movement, an offshoot of the Vienna Circle.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski's academic career in Poland was affected by his heritage.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In 1937, when he applied for a chair at Poznań University, the chair was abolished to avoid assigning it to Tarski – indisputably the strongest applicant – because he was Jewish.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski's ties to the Unity of Science movement likely saved his life, because they resulted in his being invited to address the Unity of Science Congress held in September 1939 at Harvard University.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] He left Poland in August 1939, on the last ship to sail from Poland for the United States before the German and Soviet invasion of Poland and the outbreak of World War II.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski left reluctantly, because Leśniewski had died a few months before, creating a vacancy which Tarski hoped to fill.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Oblivious to the Nazi threat, he left his wife and children in Warsaw, not to see them again until 1946.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] During the war, nearly all his Jewish extended family were murdered by the German occupiers.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In the United States, Tarski held a number of temporary teaching and research positions: at Harvard University (1939), at City College of New York (1940), and thanks to a Guggenheim Fellowship, at the Institute for Advanced Study at Princeton (1942), where he again met Gödel.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In 1942 Tarski joined the mathematics department at the University of California, Berkeley, where he spent the rest of his career.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Although emeritus from 1968, he taught until 1973 and supervised Ph.D. candidates until his death.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] He also strongly influenced the dissertations of Adolf Lindenbaum, Dana Scott, and Steven Givant.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Five of Tarski's students were women, remarkably so, given that men were then the overwhelming majority of graduate students.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] He had extramarital affairs with at least two of the women.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] After he showed the work of another female student to a male colleague, the colleague published it himself, causing the woman to break off her graduate studies and later move to a different university.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski lectured at University College, London (1950, 1966), the Institut Henri Poincaré in Paris (1955), the Miller Institute for Basic Research in Science at Berkeley (1958–60), the University of California at Los Angeles (1967), and the Pontifical Catholic University of Chile (1974–75).
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski presided over the Association for Symbolic Logic, 1944–46, and the International Union for the History and Philosophy of Science, 1956–57; and was an honorary editor of *Algebra Universalis*.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski's mathematical interests were exceptionally broad.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] His collected papers run to about 2,500 pages, most of them on mathematics, not logic.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] For a concise survey of Tarski's mathematical and logical accomplishments by his former student Solomon Feferman, see "Interludes I–VI" in Feferman and Feferman.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski's first paper, published when he was 19 years old, was on set theory, a subject to which he returned throughout his life.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In 1924, he and Stefan Banach proved that, if one accepts the Axiom of Choice, a ball can be cut into a finite number of pieces, and then reassembled into a ball of larger size, or alternatively it can be reassembled into two balls whose sizes each equal that of the original one.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] This result is now called the Banach–Tarski paradox.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In *A decision method for elementary algebra and geometry*, Tarski showed, by the method of quantifier elimination, that the first-order theory of the real numbers under addition and multiplication is decidable.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] (While this result appeared only in 1948, it dates back to 1930 and was mentioned in Tarski (1931).) This is a very curious result, because Alonzo Church proved in 1936 that Peano arithmetic (the theory of natural numbers) is *not* decidable.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Peano arithmetic is also incomplete by Gödel's incompleteness theorem.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In his 1953 *Undecidable theories*, Tarski et al. showed that many mathematical systems, including lattice theory, abstract projective geometry, and closure algebras, are all undecidable.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] The theory of Abelian groups is decidable, but that of non-Abelian groups is not.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] While teaching at the Stefan Żeromski Gimnazjum in the 1920s and 30s, Tarski often taught geometry.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Using some ideas of Mario Pieri, in 1926 Tarski devised an original axiomatization for plane Euclidean geometry, one considerably more concise than Hilbert's.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski's axioms form a first-order theory devoid of set theory, whose individuals are points, and having only two primitive relations.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In 1930, he proved this theory decidable because it can be mapped into another theory he had already proved decidable, namely his first-order theory of the real numbers.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In 1929 he showed that much of Euclidean solid geometry could be recast as a second-order theory whose individuals are *spheres* (a primitive notion), a single primitive binary relation "is contained in", and two axioms that, among other things, imply that containment partially orders the spheres.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Relaxing the requirement that all individuals be spheres yields a formalization of mereology far easier to exposit than Lesniewski's variant.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Near the end of his life, Tarski wrote a very long letter, published as Tarski and Givant (1999), summarizing his work on geometry.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In 1941, Tarski published an important paper on binary relations, which began the work on relation algebra and its metamathematics that occupied Tarski and his students for much of the balance of his life.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] While that exploration (and the closely related work of Roger Lyndon) uncovered some important limitations of relation algebra, Tarski also showed (Tarski and Givant 1987) that relation algebra can express most axiomatic set theory and Peano arithmetic.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] For an introduction to relation algebra, see Maddux (2006).
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In the late 1940s, Tarski and his students devised cylindric algebras, which are to first-order logic what the two-element Boolean algebra is to classical sentential logic.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] This work culminated in the two monographs by Tarski, Henkin, and Monk (1971, 1985).
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski's student, Robert Lawson Vaught, has ranked Tarski as one of the four greatest logicians of all time — along with Aristotle, Gottlob Frege, and Kurt Gödel.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] However, Tarski often expressed great admiration for Charles Sanders Peirce, particularly for his pioneering work in the logic of relations.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski produced axioms for *logical consequence* and worked on deductive systems, the algebra of logic, and the theory of definability.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] His semantic methods, which culminated in the model theory he and a number of his Berkeley students developed in the 1950s and 60s, radically transformed Hilbert's proof-theoretic metamathematics.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Around 1930, Tarski developed an abstract theory of logical deductions that models some properties of logical calculi.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Mathematically, what he described is just a finitary closure operator on a set (the set of *sentences*).
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In abstract algebraic logic, finitary closure operators are still studied under the name *consequence operator*, which was coined by Tarski.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] The set *S* represents a set of sentences, a subset *T* of *S* a theory, and cl(*T*) is the set of all sentences that follow from the theory.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] This abstract approach was applied to fuzzy logic (see Gerla 2000).
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski's 1936 article "On the concept of logical consequence" argued that the conclusion of an argument will follow logically from its premises if and only if every model of the premises is a model of the conclusion.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In 1937, he published a paper presenting clearly his views on the nature and purpose of the deductive method, and the role of logic in scientific studies.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] His high school and undergraduate teaching on logic and axiomatics culminated in a classic short text, published first in Polish, then in German translation, and finally in a 1941 English translation as *Introduction to Logic and to the Methodology of Deductive Sciences*.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski's 1969 "Truth and proof" considered both Gödel's incompleteness theorems and Tarski's undefinability theorem, and mulled over their consequences for the axiomatic method in mathematics.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] An English translation appeared in the 1956 first edition of the volume *Logic, Semantics, Metamathematics*.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] This collection of papers from 1923 to 1938 is an event in 20th-century analytic philosophy, a contribution to symbolic logic, semantics, and the philosophy of language.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] For a brief discussion of its content, see Convention T (and also T-schema).
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] A philosophical debate examines the extent to which Tarski's theory of truth for formalized languages can be seen as a correspondence theory of truth.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] The debate centers on how to read Tarski's condition of material adequacy for a true definition.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] as expressing merely a deflationary theory of truth or as embodying truth as a more substantial property (see Kirkham 1992).
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In 1936, Tarski published Polish and German versions of a lecture, “On the Concept of Following Logically", he had given the preceding year at the International Congress of Scientific Philosophy in Paris.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] A new English translation of this paper, Tarski (2002), highlights the many differences between the German and Polish versions of the paper and corrects a number of mistranslations in Tarski (1983).
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] This publication set out the modern model-theoretic definition of (semantic) logical consequence, or at least the basis for it.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Whether Tarski's notion was entirely the modern one turns on whether he intended to admit models with varying domains (and in particular, models with domains of different cardinalities).
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] This question is a matter of some debate in the philosophical literature.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] John Etchemendy stimulated much of the discussion about Tarski's treatment of varying domains.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski ends by pointing out that his definition of logical consequence depends upon a division of terms into the logical and the extra-logical and he expresses some skepticism that any such objective division will be forthcoming.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] "What are Logical Notions?" can thus be viewed as continuing "On the Concept of Logical Consequence".
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski's "What are Logical Notions?" (Tarski 1986) is the published version of a talk that he gave originally in 1966 in London and later in 1973 in Buffalo; it was edited without his direct involvement by John Corcoran.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] It became the most cited paper in the journal *History and Philosophy of Logic*.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In the talk, Tarski proposed demarcation of logical operations (which he calls "notions") from non-logical.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] The suggested criteria were derived from the Erlangen program of the 19th-century German mathematician Felix Klein.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Mautner (in 1946), and possibly an article by the Portuguese mathematician José Sebastião e Silva, anticipated Tarski in applying the Erlangen Program to logic.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] The Erlangen program classified the various types of geometry (Euclidean geometry, affine geometry, topology, etc.) by the type of one-one transformation of space onto itself that left the objects of that geometrical theory invariant.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] (A one-to-one transformation is a functional map of the space onto itself so that every point of the space is associated with or mapped to one other point of the space.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] So, "rotate 30 degrees" and "magnify by a factor of 2" are intuitive descriptions of simple uniform one-one transformations.) Continuous transformations give rise to the objects of topology, similarity transformations to those of Euclidean geometry, and so on.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] As the range of permissible transformations becomes broader, the range of objects one is able to distinguish as preserved by the application of the transformations becomes narrower.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Similarity transformations are fairly narrow (they preserve the relative distance between points) and thus allow us to distinguish relatively many things (e.g., equilateral triangles from non-equilateral triangles).
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Tarski's proposal was to demarcate the logical notions by considering all possible one-to-one transformations (automorphisms) of a domain onto itself.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] By domain is meant the universe of discourse of a model for the semantic theory of logic.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] *Individuals*: No individuals, provided the domain has at least two members.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] *Quantifiers*: Tarski explicitly discusses only monadic quantifiers and points out that all such numerical quantifiers are admitted under his proposal.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] These include the standard universal and existential quantifiers as well as numerical quantifiers such as "Exactly four", "Finitely many", "Uncountably many", and "Between four and 9 million", for example.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] While Tarski does not enter into the issue, it is also clear that polyadic quantifiers are admitted under the proposal.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] *Set-Theoretic relations*: Relations such as inclusion, intersection and union applied to subsets of the domain are logical in the present sense.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] *Set membership*: Tarski ended his lecture with a discussion of whether the set membership relation counted as logical in his sense.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] *Logical notions of higher order*: While Tarski confined his discussion to operations of first-order logic, there is nothing about his proposal that necessarily restricts it to first-order logic.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] (Tarski likely restricted his attention to first-order notions as the talk was given to a non-technical audience.) So, higher-order quantifiers and predicates are admitted as well.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In some ways the present proposal is the obverse of that of Lindenbaum and Tarski (1936), who proved that all the logical operations of Bertrand Russell's and Whitehead's *Principia Mathematica* are invariant under one-to-one transformations of the domain onto itself.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] The present proposal is also employed in Tarski and Givant (1987).
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Solomon Feferman and Vann McGee further discussed Tarski's proposal in work published after his death.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Feferman (1999) raises problems for the proposal and suggests a cure: replacing Tarski's preservation by automorphisms with preservation by arbitrary homomorphisms.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In essence, this suggestion circumvents the difficulty Tarski's proposal has in dealing with a sameness of logical operation across distinct domains of a given cardinality and across domains of distinct cardinalities.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Feferman's proposal results in a radical restriction of logical terms as compared to Tarski's original proposal.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] In particular, it ends up counting as logical only those operators of standard first-order logic without identity.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] Vann McGee (1996) provides a precise account of what operations are logical in the sense of Tarski's proposal in terms of expressibility in a language that extends first-order logic by allowing arbitrarily long conjunctions and disjunctions, and quantification over arbitrarily many variables.
[src:denotation/alfred-tarski] "Arbitrarily" includes a countable infinity.
[src:denotation/denotation] In philosophy and linguistics, the **denotation** of a word or expression is its strictly literal meaning.
[src:denotation/denotation] For instance, the English word "warm" denotes the property of having high temperature.
[src:denotation/denotation] Denotation is contrasted with other aspects of meaning, in particular *connotation*.
[src:denotation/denotation] For instance, the word "warm" may evoke calmness, coziness, or kindness (as in the warmth of someone's personality) but these associations are not part of the word's denotation.
[src:denotation/denotation] Similarly, an expression's denotation is separate from pragmatic inferences it may trigger.
[src:denotation/denotation] For instance, describing something as "warm" often implicates that it is not hot, but this is once again not part of the word's denotation.
[src:denotation/denotation] Denotation plays a major role in several fields.
[src:denotation/denotation] Within semantics and philosophy of language, denotation is studied as an important aspect of meaning.
[src:denotation/denotation] In mathematics and computer science, assignments of denotations to expressions are a crucial step in defining interpreted formal languages.
[src:denotation/denotation] The main task of formal semantics is to reverse engineer the computational system which assigns denotations to expressions of natural languages.
[src:denotation/denotation] In natural language semantics, denotations are conceived of as the outputs of the semantic component of the grammar.
[src:denotation/denotation] For example, the denotation of the word "blue" is the property of being blue and the denotation of the word "Barack Obama" is the person who goes by that name.
[src:denotation/denotation] Phrases also have denotations which are computed according to the principle of compositionality.
[src:denotation/denotation] For instance, the verb phrase "passed the class" denotes the property of having passed the class.
[src:denotation/denotation] Depending on one's particular theory of semantics, denotations may be identified either with terms' extensions, intensions, or other structures such as context change potentials.
[src:denotation/denotation] When uttered in discourse, expressions may convey other associations which are not computed by the grammar and thus are not part of its denotation.
[src:denotation/denotation] For instance, depending on the context, saying "I ran five miles" may convey that you ran exactly five miles and not more.
[src:denotation/denotation] This content is not part of the sentence's denotation but rather pragmatic inferences arrived at by applying social cognition to its denotation.
[src:denotation/denotation] Linguistic discussion of the differences between denotation, meaning, and reference is rooted in the work of Ferdinand de Saussure, specifically in his theory of semiotics written in the book Course in General Linguistics.
[src:denotation/denotation] Philosophers Gottlob Frege and Bertrand Russell have also made influential contributions to this subject.
[src:denotation/denotation] Although they have similar meanings, denotation should not be confused with reference.
[src:denotation/denotation] A reference is a specific person, place, or thing that a speaker identifies when using a word.
[src:denotation/denotation] Vocabulary from John Searle's speech act theory can be used to define this relationship.
[src:denotation/denotation] According to this theory, the speaker's action of identifying a person, place, or thing is called referring.
[src:denotation/denotation] The specific person, place, or thing identified by the speaker is called the referent.
[src:denotation/denotation] Reference itself captures the relationship between the referent and the word or phrase used by the speaker.
[src:denotation/denotation] For referring expressions, the denotation of the phrase is most likely the phrase's referent.
[src:denotation/denotation] For content words, the denotation of the word can refer to any object, real or imagined, to which the word could be applied.
[src:denotation/denotation] In "On Sense and Reference", philosopher Gottlob Frege distinguished so-called *Sinn*, translated as sense, from *Bedeutung*, translated as reference or denotation when he evaluated words like the German "Morgenstern" and "Abendstern".
[src:denotation/denotation] The translations of the German terminology differ, as past translators have proposed *meaning* to refer to *Sinn* as well as *Bedeutung*, with a strong contemporary preference to interpret *meaning* as a possible translation of *Bedeutung*.
[src:denotation/denotation] Author Thomas Herbst uses the words "kid" and "child" to illustrate the same concept.
[src:denotation/denotation] According to Herbst, these two words have the same denotation, as they have the same member set; however, "kid" may be used in an informal speech situation whereas "child" may be used in a more formal speech situation.
